# Coding Standards

## 1. Variable Naming — No Short Meaningless Names

All variable, parameter, and function names must be at least 4 characters and descriptive.

```typescript
// BAD
const s = 'hello';
const cb = () => {};
items.map((e) => e.name);
const d = new Date();
const i = 0;

// GOOD
const message = 'hello';
const callback = () => {};
items.map((item) => item.name);
const date = new Date();
const index = 0;
```

Single-letter exceptions allowed ONLY in:
- Generic type parameters: `<T>`, `<K, V>`
- Unused event params required by API: `(_event, value) =>`

## 2. Arrow Functions Only

Use arrow functions for all declarations. The `function` keyword is only allowed when `this` binding is required (e.g., class methods, Mocha-style tests).

```typescript
// BAD
function calculateRate(total, passed) { ... }
function MyComponent() { ... }

// GOOD
const calculateRate = (total: number, passed: number) => { ... };
const MyComponent: React.FC = () => { ... };
```

React components should use `const Name: React.FC = () => (...)`.

## 3. No Inline Styling

All styles must be in CSS files. Do not use the `style` prop on JSX elements.

```tsx
// BAD
<div style={{ marginTop: 16, color: 'red' }}>text</div>

// GOOD — use CSS classes
<div className="app-mt-md app-text-danger">text</div>
```

Add classes to `packages/client/src/styles/app.css` using PatternFly CSS variables for consistency.
